donating their marrow or not. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
So make the possible donor the mother or the father if you wish... the principle still applies. No person can be forced to use their body to keep another person alive, even when that person is responsible for the creation of that life. And when you get right down to it, it is a very personal right that nobody in their right mind would want to give up, even though it is a right that is abused by some.<br>
<br>
Look, don't think for a minute that I like abortion - I don't. Too many fucktards use abortion as a form of birth control. But the sad fact is that many of these children are lucky they got aborted, because the fucktards who conceived them would give them a terrible shot at life, even if they were to survive past puberty.<br>
<br>
I don't grieve too much though, because in actuality, the fetus is not what most consider a person - a human yes, but a person. A fetus is not self aware, does not have any dreams, desires or goals. They will never miss life anymore than a person who is braindead would. That's not to say they don't have the potential to have all these things, but potential is like good intentions... until it solidifies, it's just vapor with no substance.<br>
<br>
The people I feel bad for are the ones who lived long enough to become self aware, to develope dreams and goals and to have families. Those are the people who really lose something at death. A fetus never was self aware, so their death is not a tragedy... at least not from their standpoint.<br>
<br>
IMO, life is not simply respiration... that is only the vehicle that carries life. Life is in the mind, not the body. You can lose an arm, leg, kidney or whatever and still be you. If the mind is gone (or never devoloped as in the case of a fetus) than there is no you - just a complex biological machine.<br>
