<br>
Until you are self aware, yes, you are just a complex biological machine. However you are able to sustain yourself outside of the womb, so no, it is not alright to kill you. If it somehow came to be a choice between letting a self aware adult die or an infant who has no self awareness, I think the person with self awareness has more of a claim to life.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>You say you believe in animal rights, in general... yet (in general) animals are not self aware. While the argument could possibly be made for dolphins, monkeys, and some more intelligent dogs etc., does that mean that killing offhand animals who are obviously not self aware is perfectly ok? </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Dogs and cats dream, which means they are indeed self aware. Maybe not in the same way that we are, but only animals with high level brain function dream. Even if they were not, this is not about killing. I am not saying it's alright to kill anything outside of the womb. I am only saying that nobody, including a mother, can be forced to use their body to keep another person alive and that if it does came down to a choice, I would go with the self aware being.<br>
<br>
Self aware or not, nobody has the right kill anything, unless it's for survival or self defense (morally speaking of course - in reality there are no rules except those that we create for ourselves). <p><br>
